comments.body:
Windows 10 Build 14393 is from 2016 which is most likely not marked as comptaible with .NET core and as @vexx32 says it will load in an implicit remoting session. AFAIK it was in Server 2019 that the ActiveDirectory module was updated to support .NET Core and will run natively in PowerShell. Any of it's operations are run in a separate process and runspace and does not have access to any of your vars so it won't be able to find `$employeeNumber` when it converts that scriptblock to the LDAP filter. A third option not mentioned is to run the cmdlet and store the variable in that runspace like

```powershell
$employeeNumber = "000"

$winSession = New-PSSession -UseWindowsPowerShell
try {
    Invoke-Command -Session $winSession -ScriptBlock {
        # $using:employeeNumber will tell PowerShell to get the value from the outside Runspace
        $employeeNumber = $using:employeeNumber
        Get-ADUser -Filter {employeeNumber -eq $employeeNumber} | select name
    }
}
finally {
    $winSession | Remove-PSSession
}
```
